AEGIS-X Cloud Posture Dashboard
PMT Candidate Submission  ·  Option 1: Cloud Posture Dashboard
James A. Bex  |  AI Architect & Governance Leader  |  Go Cloud Careers |  CSA STAR for AI
May 29, 2026
                      








01  Problem Statement

Security engineers managing multi-cloud environments have no unified view of misconfigurations across AWS, GCP, and Azure. They toggle between three native consoles with incompatible severity scales, no normalized policy layer, and no shared audit trail. The result: high MTTD, fragmented compliance posture, and critical findings that sit open because they are buried in noise.
Three root causes drive the problem:
No normalized severity model across providers — the same misconfiguration receives different severity labels on different platforms, making cross-account prioritization impossible.
No unified policy enforcement layer — without OPA/Rego applied consistently, policy drift goes undetected until a scan or audit surfaces it.
No immutable audit trail — remediation history lives in Slack threads and spreadsheets, not a forensically sound record.

User Persona
Marcus T. — Cloud Security Engineer  |  5 yrs experience  |  3-account AWS/GCP/Azure environment  |  FedRAMP audit owner

Goals
Single pane of glass across all accounts
Risk-ranked findings, not native severity noise
Audit report in under 10 minutes

Pain Points
3 consoles, 3 severity scales, 0 unified view
Remediation history scattered across Slack and email
Cannot answer "what is our posture right now"



02  Proposed Features & Screen Flow

Three screens take Marcus from situational awareness to closed finding without leaving the platform.
Screen Core Features AEGIS-X Component
Screen 1Posture Overview
Cross-account misconfiguration count + severity delta
Posture score per account (0–100, compliance-weighted)
Service category breakdown — IAM, storage, network, encryption
Filter bar: provider, severity, account, framework, tag
OPA/Rego policy engine + normalized severity scoring across AWS Config, GCP SCC, Azure Defender
Screen 2Findings Table
Sortable table: resource, account, severity, rule, framework, age
Inline expand: OPA rule, resource config, remediation recommendation
Bulk actions: assign owner, accept risk, suppress, create ticket (Jira/ServiceNow)
GEN-SHIELD DevSecOps pipeline output + STAR CAR-D 20-domain compliance mapping
Screen 3Remediation Panel
Full finding detail: resource ID, account, timestamp, severity breakdown
Compliance panel: FedRAMP, EU AI Act, NIST CSF, STAR CAR-D control mapping
One-click remediation with dry-run preview + immutable audit log + one-click export
cATO workflow + tamper-evident audit log + STAR CAR-D compliance export engine



03  Prioritization

Every feature was evaluated against one test: does this reduce Marcus's time-to-action on a critical finding? Features that do not serve that test are deferred.
Tier
Feature
Rationale
What It Unlocks
P0Now
Posture overview, normalized severity scoring, cross-account filter bar
Answers the first question: what is broken right now? Without this, nothing downstream functions.
Eliminates console-switching. Establishes posture baseline for trend tracking.
P1Next
Findings table, inline triage, bulk actions, compliance framework mapping
Turns awareness into action. Compliance mapping connects findings to business obligations, not just technical hygiene.
Bulk actions cut per-finding handling time from minutes to seconds.
P2Later
Remediation executor, dry-run enforcement, audit export, automated ticket creation
High value but requires trust in the system first. Auto-remediation on an untrusted platform creates incidents.
Closes the loop from finding to resolution to audit record. Unlocks cATO pathway.


Intentionally deferred:
AI-generated remediation scripts, ML-based predictive risk scoring, multi-user commenting, and mobile-first design. All are valid long-term capabilities. None reduce MTTD at MVP.


